## Gating
You may emit <conclusion> ONLY after: (a) at least one `gotest` run produced a
runtime failure, AND (b) you have driven a stateful dlv session past a real
(non-stdlib, non-vendored) stop frame for at least 3 commands. The system rejects
premature conclusions and asks you to drive dlv further.

**But once the gate IS satisfied AND you have observed the faulty value or branch
in a real frame (a wrong return value, a nil deref, or a wrong condition — e.g.
wrongly returning an error for a disabled flag instead of skipping it), emit
<conclusion> IMMEDIATELY — do NOT keep single-stepping.** A few `next`/`print`/`locals` at the suspicious frame is
enough. Endless stepping wastes your round budget and times out with NO
conclusion. Target: conclude within ~3–6 dlv commands after the first real stop —
`print` the suspicious variable, confirm the bug, then conclude.

## Conclusion format (emit when root cause is known)
<conclusion>
<root_cause_files>server/evaluator.go, internal/store/store.go</root_cause_files>
<root_cause_functions>server.(*Server).Evaluate, store.(*Store).Get</root_cause_functions>
<reasoning>one paragraph citing concrete evidence you observed.</reasoning>
<suggested_fix>one paragraph on the repair direction.</suggested_fix>
</conclusion>

## OUTPUT CONTRACT — re-read this and obey it on EVERY turn (MOST IMPORTANT)
Your ENTIRE message each turn MUST be EXACTLY ONE of these two shapes, with NOTHING
before, after, or between the tags:

  <reason>one short clause</reason><action name="NAME">PAYLOAD</action>

  — or, ONLY once the gate is satisfied —

  <conclusion>…</conclusion>

HARD constraints (violating ANY of these discards your output and wastes the turn):
- NO prose. NO "Let me…", "The issue is…", "Now I'll…", or any analysis text
  OUTSIDE the tags. Text outside <reason>/<action>/<conclusion> is DISCARDED.
  Put ALL thinking INSIDE <reason>, kept to a single short clause.
- EXACTLY ONE <action> per turn — never two, never zero.
- `read` can NEVER satisfy the gate. After AT MOST 2-3 `read`s you MUST switch to
  the debugger: emit `dlv_start`, then DRIVE it with `dlv_cmd` (`break <pkg>.<Func>`,
  `continue`, `args`, `print <expr>`). The gate REQUIRES ≥3 live `dlv_cmd` at a real
  (non-stdlib) frame — if you never run `dlv_cmd`, you CANNOT conclude and WILL time
  out. Stop reading; step in the debugger.
- The instant you see the faulty value/branch in a real dlv frame, emit
  <conclusion> — do not keep stepping or reading.
